A_DESCRIPTION:
Two non-functional chimneys will be removed in order to move the houses. Rebuilding of the chimneys may not be feasible;however,if technically feasible the central chimney will be restored. The secondary chimney currently presents structural problems (it bears upon the ceiling joists in the original parlor and does not extend to the floor, currently causing 2" of negative deflection of that ceiling) and will not be restored. 

Shed roof on 1990 addition to 507 Yancey Street currently creates a drainage problem; slope of roof may be changed/steepened to improve drainage; this will not be visible from the street and will not change the footprint of the existing shed roof or the house. Foundation will be parged CMU or poured concrete on the sides and rear as it is currently. Brick will be utilized on the front of the house, either as structural material or as a veneer.

A_PROJECT_NAME: 2116 West Club Blvd - Addition and Modifications
A_DESCRIPTION:
We are proposing to update and expand a 1930s single-family residence located at 2116 W. Club Blvd., a brick Tudor style structure that is considered "contributing" to the Watts-Hillandale Historic District. 
The proposed expansion would first require demolishing (to the foundation) an approximately 270 SF single-story form at the rear of the house which currently includes the kitchen, butler's pantry, and rear entry foyer. One of our goals has been to maintain as much of the existing structure's footprint as possible. Therefore, we are only proposing to minimally increase the footprint of the home. 
The proposed addition would include about 380 SF of conditioned space on the first floor in order to accommodate a larger, more functional family entertaining area that is connected to the kitchen. Other proposed modifications to the first floor include the conversion of a 143 SF conditioned sun room back into an unconditioned porch that is to be screened. 
The proposed expansion would also add another 380 SF of conditioned space to the second floor. The additional space upstairs would accommodate a new laundry room and master suite, including a walk-in closet and full bathroom. 
The modifications as proposed above would transform an existing 3 bedroom, 1.5 bathroom house into a 4 bedroom, 3.5 bathroom house with more flexible living/entertaining spaces. The proposed changes would not only allow the house to better serve the current homeowners but would also offer more value to future buyers.
Creator: gisproc_sys

A_DESCRIPTION:
Note:  Multiple Locations - Used 101 City Hall Plaza as Address

This Major Certificate of Appropriateness seeks to ensure suitability of design of several components of the new Downtown Durham Wayfinding Project. The new wayfinding system will replace the existing disconnected signage throughout Downtown, at multiple locations within public rights-of-way. 

The intent of the Downtown Wayfinding Project is to provide a consistent design for signage elements and a comprehensive and coordinated approach to wayfinding throughout Downtown 
for motorists, pedestrians, and bicyclists alike. Each of the elements that we are seeking a Major COA for provide a valuable step in a visitors journey. 

Other goals of the project are to help market Durham's assets, present a friendly image and communicate that the city is efficient, organized and caring. The project will also provide a design standard that fits the environment and reduces signage clutter throughout Downtown Durham.
Creator: gisproc_sys

A_DESCRIPTION:
The house located at 829 Clarendon Street is a Non-Contributing Property located in the Trinity Heights Local Historic District. The house was built in 2002 in the style of a 1920's Craftsman 
House. In 2008, a detached 2-car garage with apartment suite was added to the property. The current owners purchased the house in June of 2011. 

The classification of construction work is to provide a two-story addition to the back of the house and renovate the existing master bathroom. The addition will consist of a Sun Room with new wood burning fireplace on the main floor. The second-floor addition consist of a new master closet with an office/sleeping room. The existing window in the second-floor hall bath gets relocated towards the house interior to allow for the second-floor addition to share the same exterior wall as the main floor addition. The master bathroom interior renovation does not affect the existing exterior. Our proposed house addition complies with the Historic 
Properties Local Review Criteria under Residential Non-Contributing Properties. The proposed house addition makes no changes to the street facing elevations.
Creator: gisproc_sys

A_DESCRIPTION:
We are proposing to demolish a "non-contributing" single-family dwelling built in the 1920s, along with a detached aluminum storage shed, located at 1509 Maryland Avenue in the WattsHillandale Historic District. The house is a wood-framed structure on a common red brick foundation, with aluminum horizontal lap siding covering the original wood. Asphalt shingles cover the gabled roof. 

Prior to, or in conjunction with the demolition of the house, existing utility lines (natural gas, water/sewer, and overhead electrical service) are to be appropriately terminated and/or removed. We intend to salvage any original building materials that have potential for reuse in a new structure. Following demolition of the existing structures, the site is to be stabilized with grass seed and straw. 

Based on the following information, demolition of the existing structures was identified as the first step toward developing this property more appropriately, for the benefit of the owners of 1509 Maryland Avenue as well as the owners of neighboring properties.

A_DESCRIPTION:
The house at 1209 Virginia is a late 1920s Classical style house that contributes to the Watts-Hillandale Historic District. Later modifications were made to the house in the 1960s, and the house has not been updated since that time. Our project is two-fold as we work to modernize and restore original character to the house in a way that is appropriate for the district and its contributing structure status. 

First, we hope to modernize the house with the addition of a central air and heating system, and a single story 457 square foot addition which will make a downstairs master suite, laundry room and pantry possible. Original house is 2,481 square feet. 

Second, we intend to restore original character to the house by removing later exterior modifications including air conditioning window units, aluminum siding, metal railings and posts on front facing porch and tile porch floor. The elements will be replaced or restored with new materials appropriate for the historic district.
Creator: gisproc_sys

A_DESCRIPTION:
The connected structure at 115 Market Street (at the corner with Chapel Hill Street) is a series of buildings bound by Market Street, Chapel Hill Street, and Main Street and identified as the former Herald-Sun complex. Visually appearing to be separate buildings of various construction types and styles, several portions of the original construction have additionally been altered over time and do not retain their apparent original architectural style. Although this series of buildings is connected and contained within one parcel, the Downtown Durham Historic District appears to identify separate portions of the property as a local Landmark (117 Market Street), Contributing (133 Chapel Hill Street) and Non-Contributing structures (115 and 123 Market Street). The owner, Self Help (via an LLC), identifies the building as the Bull City Business Center.

This project seeks to alter the street level of 123 Market Street (identified on the adjacent diagram as non-contributing) to create additional street level, sidewalk addressing interior space by converting an existing office suite into separate tenants with new entrances with associated canopies and signage.
As part of this work, a single existing entrance within the portion of the building at 117 Market Street will also be minimally altered. A portion of 136 Chapel Hill Street, which appears incorrectly identified as contributing within Appendix A of the preservation plan (it appears to be identified by the map on page 41 as non-contributing and stylistically appears to be part of the building at 123 Market Street) will receive similar treatment at one existing entrance and one additional proposed entrance.
Creator: gisproc_sys

A_DESCRIPTION:
The 617 Morehead Avenue project entails a single story addition to the east (side) and South (rear) of the existing structure. This will entail, additional site work as well, consisting of reworked parking area to the rear of the structure as well as ADA accessible routes to the entrances of the building. Some minor repairs to the existing wood trim, columns and fascia will also be considered. 

The addition will fill in an existing void, connecting a single story portion of the building at the rear, to a single story sun room to the side/east. The new structure will use similar materials to keep within the existing design context while using a stepped/offset fac;ade to delineate the original structure from the new.

A_DESCRIPTION:
At the South facade, there are two original steel windows that we propose to be modified.
a. East of the main entrance, we propose removing the entire steel window system in a single bay. The masonry sill and lower wall will also be removed. A new painted metal and glass sectional garage door will fill the existing opening. The intent is to maintain and reflect the existing masonry opening. 

b. West of the main entrance, half of one of the steel window systems will be removed from top to bottom. The masonry sill below this half will also be removed. The heavier vertical mullion central to this pair of windows will remain. A new narrow stile painted metal and glass door and storefront will this half of the opening.

At the North facade, there is a single original steel windows that we propose to be changed. 
a. To the far east of the main entrance, half of one of the steel window systems will be removed from top to bottom. The masonry sill below this half will also be removed. A_PROJECT_NAME: 2108 West Club Boulevard - New Construction, Addition, Modifications Demolition and Site Work
A_DESCRIPTION:
Siding:The existing aluminum siding will be removed on the upper story to expose original wood lap siding. Original siding will be scraped and painted. After- siding is removed, contractor will look for ghost marks of possible brackets or- other exter-ior- details, and these will be reconstrncted. Eaves will be unboxed to expose rafter- tails. 

Windows: All original windows on the fo-st story will be repair-ed. Non-or-iginal louvered window over- the kitchen sink will be replaced with wood nine-over-one windows to match original.The original 12-light casement windows wer-e found in the garage, however they are in ver-y poor condition and likely cannot be r-epaired. New 12-light wood casement windows sized to the existing opening will replace the non-original sliding windows on the second story. New addition windows will be wood double hung nine-over--one, except for a pair of wood casement windows on the rear and an upper- stor-y bathroom window. 

Addition: New addition on the rear with kitchen, mudroom, laundry. master bath and screened porch on the fost floor and closet and bathroom on the second. Addition material to be wood lap siding to match second story siding, including corner boards and any hidden details. 

Porch: Non-original front porch columns and railing will be removed. Craftsman style f ont porch with tapered columns on brick piers and wood railing will be installed. Original front door will be restored with glass replaced in the upper portion. Existing original door will be repaired 

Garage: Garage is in poor condition and will be demolished. New garage will be constructed with typical frame construction on a brick-veneered concrete stem wall.  Exterior to be covered with flat wood lap siding  (to match primary structure), exposed rafters, and notched door frame to match the existing structure.  Roof to be 5V metal.
Creator: gisproc_sys

A_DESCRIPTION:
Project involves replacement of the existing wooden dogear shadowbox fence with a more traditional dogear vertical board fence.  The current fence was installed sometime in the last 25 years and is not an original element of the property.   There is significant damage to a number of the boxed sections on all sides of the yard, including two full sections of the rear (west) fence being knocked down by a tree trunk.  Due to the nature of the fence's construction (shadowboxed panels joined at vertical posts) and the location of the damaged panels, it is not feasible to repair the sections in place.  Therefore, we are proposing to replace the entire 6-foot tall fence along the entire north and western border and approximately the rear 2/3 of the southern border of the property, a total of approximately 488 linear feet of fencing.  There is an existing rear gate in approximately the middle of the rear (west) fence line and we intend to replace this as well with a new gate that will have the same dimensions and scale as the existing gate.  It has been recommended to us that we keep a gate at the rear fence so that maintenance and plant control will be easier and more efficient.
The new fence will be of the same construction as the existing one, in terms of scale, size, height, location, and materials used.
Creator: gisproc_sys

A_DESCRIPTION: In October 2017, about 6 weeks after purchase, I had a 4 foot wooden stockade dog-ear fence installed around the front yard, including two 4 foot gates (one at the front walkway and one near the front porch. At the back of the house, I had a 6 foot wooden stockade dog-ear privacy fence installed between my home and the one next door (with which I share a driveway), although the rear fence cannot be seen from the road. I chose this fence style because it most closely matched the 8-10 foot privacy fence  installed by the previous owner along the northeast and southern side of the property as well as the back deck and planters. My main objective in fencing the front yard was safety, not privacy. My plan has always been to paint the fence white, add oversize finials to the 4x4 posts, plant azaleas and Mexican petunias on the inside of the fence and groundcover outside of the fence on the outside of the sidewalk as well as create a fenced off space for my garbage and recycling cans at the northeast corner of my front yard.
Creator: gisproc_sys

A_DESCRIPTION:
A.Project Intent and Background Statement

A_PROJECT_NAME: 2032 West Club Blvd - New Construction and Site Work
A_DESCRIPTION:
The property is the Bowden-Arena House. It is a two and a half story wood framed craftsman style house and was built in 1919. It is generally in excellent condition and has most of its original windows, trim, and details including deep overhangs and heavy timber brackets.

Four years ago, the front porch was restored and expanded, a new screened porch and deck were added to the east side, and a new brick walkway to the front porch was constructed. This work was all part of a previous COA.

Two years ago, the non-historic garage and breezeway roof were removed, and a new addition was added to the north end of the home. This addition included a mud room, two side porches, and a two-car garage with living space above. The driveway was re-built in its existing location, with an 8,000-gallon cistern below ground. This work was all part of another COA.

The current proposal is for new landscaping and site improvements to make the site more livable for
the owners and their children. The scope includes a new playhouse, a hot tub and brick terrace, small garden shed, potting table, compost bins, a cold frame, fences, low  stone wall, grading and drainage in the east yard, and trees and plants.

At the east side of the front walk steps, the existing 6 x 6 timber wall was shortened and Lincoln Creek Stone strips were used to retain/tier the span where the timbers were removed.
